Q4.

(a)267/79=3 ... 30

gcd(267,79)=gcd(79,30)

79/30=2 ... 19

gcd(79,30)=gcd(30,19)

30/19=1 ... 11

gcd(30,19)=gcd(19,11)

19/11=1 ... 8

gcd(19,11)=gcd(11,8)

11/8=1 ... 3

gcd(11,8)=gcd(8,3)

8/3=2 ... 2

gcd(8,3)=gcd(3,2)=1

Therefore gcd(267,79)=1, they are relatively prime

(b)1=3−(8−2∗3)=3∗3−8

3∗3−8=3∗(11−1∗8)−8=3∗11−4∗8

3∗11−4∗8=3∗11−4∗(19−11)=7∗11−4∗19

7∗11−4∗19=7∗(30−19)−4∗19=7∗30−11∗19

7∗30−11∗19=7∗30−11∗(79−2∗30)=29∗30−11∗79

29∗30−11∗79=29∗(267−3∗79)−11∗79=29∗267−98∗79

Therefore 1=29∗267−98∗79

Q5.

Assume a=p1a1p2a2 ... pnan, b=p1b1p2b2 ... pnbn, y=p1y1p2y2 ... pnyn

Then gcd(a,b)=p1min(a1,b1)p2min(a2,b2) ... pnmin(an,bn)

gcd(gcd(a,b),y)=p1min(a1,b1,y1)p2min(a2,b2,y2) ... pnmin(an,bn,yn)

gcd(a,y)=d1=p1min(a1,y1)p2min(a2,y2) ... pnmin(an,yn)

gcd(b,y)=d2=p1min(b1,y1)p2min(b2,y2) ... pnmin(bn,yn)

gcd(d1,d2)=p1min(a1,b1,y1)p2min(a2,b2,y2) ... pnmin(an,bn,yn)

Therefore gcd(gcd(a,b),y)=gcd(d1,d2)

Q14.

Assume c=gcd(a,m)

Then we have c|a and c|m

∃p,q∈Z((pc=a)∧(qc=m))

∵a≡b(mod m)

∃k∈Z(a−b=km)

So b=c(p−kq)

Thus c|b

Therefore gcd(a,m)≤gcd(b,m)

By an analogous argument we can get gcd(b,m)≤gcd(a,m)

Therefore gcd(a,m)=gcd(b,m)

Q17.

When gcd(M,pq)>1

We have gcd(M,p)=p,gcd(M,q)=q or gcd(M,p)=1,gcd(M,q)=q or gcd(M,p)=p,gcd(M,q)=1

de≡1(mod (p−1)(q−1))

Cd≡(Me)d(mod pq)≡M1+k(p−1)(q−1)(mod n)

WLOG, consider the case gcd(M,p)=p,gcd(M,q)=1

Cd≡M1+k(p−1)(q−1)(mod p)≡0(mod p)≡M(mod p)

Cd≡M∗(Mq−1)k(p−1)(mod q)≡M(mod q)

Since gcd(p,q)=1, Cd≡M(mod n) by Chinese remainder Theorem.
